# Step 1 — User Opens Website

Example visitor request:

```id="jvyrzq"
https://client1.platform-domain.com
```

The browser begins resolving the domain.

---

# Step 2 — DNS Resolution

The browser queries DNS.

```id="b0v6g4"
client1.platform-domain.com
```

DNS provider:

```id="3ui8ld"
AWS Route53
```

DNS returns the platform endpoint.

Example:

```id="m1uv34"
Application Load Balancer IP
```

Now the browser knows where to send the request.

---

# Step 3 — CDN / Security Layer

The request first reaches:

```id="rjld6s"
Cloudflare / CloudFront
```

This layer provides:

* DDoS protection
* caching
* TLS termination
* bot filtering

If cached content exists, it may respond immediately.

Otherwise the request continues.

---

# Step 4 — Load Balancer

The request reaches the platform entry point.

```id="7u7o3j"
AWS Application Load Balancer
```

Purpose:

* distribute traffic
* route requests to healthy servers

Example distribution:

```id="pzw48u"
EC2 instance A
EC2 instance B
```

Load balancing prevents overload on a single server.

---

# Step 5 — Reverse Proxy Layer

On the server, the request hits:

```id="49a2f7"
Nginx reverse proxy
```

Nginx determines which container should handle the request.

Example routing rule:

```id="cavgy2"
client1.platform-domain.com
      ↓
wordpress-client1 container
```

Another domain:

```id="q5eshu"
client2.platform-domain.com
      ↓
wordpress-client2 container
```

---

# Step 6 — WordPress Container

The selected container processes the request.

Inside the container:

```id="o82l3d"
PHP runtime
WordPress core
plugins
themes
```

WordPress prepares the page content.

---

# Step 7 — Cache Layer

Before hitting the database, WordPress checks cache.

Example:

```id="z2fcbp"
Redis object cache
```

If cached data exists:

```id="u6ywm5"
response returned immediately
```

This reduces database queries.

---

# Step 8 — Database Query

If data is not cached, WordPress queries the database.

Database service:

```id="xnx1tt"
AWS RDS MySQL
```

Example query:

```id="g6m7ke"
SELECT * FROM posts
```

The database returns content.

---

# Step 9 — Media Retrieval

Images and files are served from object storage.

Storage:

```id="bxfm3o"
AWS S3
```

Example:

```id="jpt4s6"
blog-image.jpg
```

This prevents large media from loading the application server.

---

# Step 10 — Response Returned to User

WordPress generates the final HTML page.

Response flow:

```id="o2e0yz"
WordPress container
      ↓
Nginx
      ↓
Load Balancer
      ↓
CDN
      ↓
User browser
```

The website renders in the browser.

---

# Complete Request Path

Full path:

```id="8wq3t7"
User Browser
      ↓
DNS (Route53)
      ↓
CDN / Cloudflare
      ↓
Application Load Balancer
      ↓
Nginx Reverse Proxy
      ↓
WordPress Container
      ↓
Redis Cache
      ↓
RDS Database
      ↓
S3 Storage
```

---

# What Happens During High Traffic

Caching layers reduce load.

Example traffic handling:

```id="sbhhy6"
1000 requests
↓
900 served from CDN
80 served from Redis cache
20 reach database
```

This dramatically improves performance.

---

# Why This Flow Matters

Engineers use this to reason about:

* latency
* bottlenecks
* failure points
* scaling strategies

If any layer fails, the platform must handle it.

---

# Reality Check

Many beginner projects show:

```id="a4o5v0"
browser → server → database
```

Your platform architecture demonstrates:

* layered request processing
* caching strategies
* traffic distribution
* infrastructure abstraction

This level of thinking aligns with **production web platform design**.

---

If you want, the next useful exercise is **mapping the exact request flow during a failure scenario** (for example: database failure or container crash). That shows how resilient the architecture is.
